DESCRIPTION
Update the dogfood capture protocol and dev workflow conventions so every review gate records structured reviewer results. This should replace prose-only gate summaries as the durable source of truth while still allowing human-readable notes.

Acceptance:
- runbook names the structured capture step for each gate attempt
- reviewer seat conventions specify harness/provider/model values for Opus, Gemini, Codex, and pilms
- pi/pilms is explicitly captured with provider=lmstudio and model=qwen/qwen3.6-35b-a3b
- process covers reruns, empty outputs, auth failures, quota failures, and disregarded malfunctioning seats
- at least one new dogfood run demonstrates structured gate reviewer records

DESIGN
## Plan

**Approach:** This bead is docs/process + one small self-contained helper script + one
demonstration capture. It does NOT touch the Go `capture-gate` code (shipped in .2). Three
moves: (1) extend the dogfood docs so every gate attempt now ALSO emits a structured
`GateAttempt` JSON and runs `etude capture-gate` against the bead's run ref — making structured
records the durable source of truth, with prose notes kept as a human-readable mirror; (2) add a
thin wrapper script `scripts/dogfood-gate-capture.sh` that builds etude fresh, sanity-checks the
run exists, runs `capture-gate --gate-file`, VERIFIES the local append, and only then pushes the
ref — lowest-friction for the autonomous /loop because the orchestrator already holds every seat's
verdict/feedback/provider at gate time and only has to hand-author one JSON doc per attempt; (3)
demonstrate it on THIS bead's OWN new dogfood run — `refs/etude/runs/etude-roadmap.2.4`, created
by .4's normal post-close dogfood-capture — by encoding .4's OWN real gate attempt(s) (its plan
gate, incl. the codex+gemini BLOCK→rerun and pilms disregarded, plus its implement+final gate) as
`GateAttempt`s and appending them via the new script. This is a genuinely NEW run (satisfies "a
new dogfood run demonstrates structured gate reviewer records") AND real production dogfood data
(not synthetic), and it dogfoods the new capability on the very bead that introduces it.
Backfilling PRE-EXISTING runs (roadmap.2.2 etc.) is explicitly bead .5's scope, NOT this bead.
Gate JSON authored by hand (NOT a generated assembler): a GateAttempt is small and the
orchestrator writes it once per attempt; a generator script would be more surface for no payoff.
dogfood-capture.sh is left UNCHANGED — stage capture runs once post-close, gates run per-attempt
at gate time (a different lifecycle), so gate capture is a separate script, not a new step bolted
onto the stage script.

**Files:**
- `docs/plans/dogfood/review-gate-runbook.md` - extend the existing "Recording Results" section:
  after the prose-note block, add a "Structured capture (etude capture-gate)" subsection naming
  the per-attempt step (emit gate JSON -> `scripts/dogfood-gate-capture.sh <bead> <gate.json>`),
  documenting the exact snake_case gate-file shape (gate_id `<phase>.r<round>`, phase, round,
  tier, status pass|rerun|escalated, reviewed_stages with real stage names + artifact shas or
  name-only `artifact:""`, seats, decision, timestamp), the REVIEWER-SEAT CONVENTIONS table
  (acceptance #2) pinning harness/provider/model per seat, and the per-outcome verdict mapping
  (acceptance #3): GO->go(+optional), BLOCK->block(+required, status rerun, next round = new
  attempt with round+1), auth/quota failure->failed(+failure_note), empty completion->empty
  (+failure_note), root-caused outage->malfunction(+failure_note), autonomous-loop skip->
  disregarded(+failure_note AND decision.degraded_reason). State explicitly that `failure_note` is
  REQUIRED for every non-go/block verdict (failed/empty/malfunction/disregarded) — the schema's
  validateGate enforces this, and the convention must say so, so seats like pilms always carry
  both `failure_note` (what broke) and `decision.degraded_reason` (why the gate still passed).
  Cross-link from "Reruns" (each rerun = a new GateAttempt, round incremented) and note prose
  notes remain the human mirror, structured is the source of truth. Add a one-line note that a
  COMBINED gate (e.g. "Implement+Final") is modeled as a single GateAttempt whose `phase`/`gate_id`
  names the dominant phase and whose `reviewed_stages` lists the artifacts it actually reviewed
  (e.g. implement+verify) — a deliberate modeling choice, not "the implement gate only".
- `docs/plans/dogfood/capture-protocol.md` - in the existing "Review Gate Capture" section, add
  that gate results are ALSO captured structurally via `etude capture-gate` (append-only to the
  run ref, one GateAttempt per attempt) and point to the runbook's conventions; keep the prose
  block as the human-readable mirror. Note this is now the import-ready structured form (replaces
  the "future import" hand-parsing of prose for gates).
- `scripts/dogfood-gate-capture.sh` (NEW) - self-contained: usage `<bead-id> <gate-json-file>`;
  builds etude fresh to a mktemp bindir (mirrors dogfood-capture.sh; never uses an ambient
  binary), `git fetch`es the run ref then verifies it exists (so capture-gate's ExpectedOld CAS
  guards against a stale tip and fails loudly rather than clobbering), runs `"$bin" capture-gate
  --run <bead> --gate-file <file>` (LOCAL append). Then — BEFORE pushing — VERIFIES the local
  result: read back the manifest via `git cat-file -p refs/etude/runs/<bead>:manifest.json | python3`
  (NOT `run show --json`, which does not exist), assert `manifest_version == 3` and the appended
  gate_id is present, and echo the resolved tip + gate count; exit non-zero if the assertion fails.
  ONLY after local verification passes does it `git push origin refs/etude/runs/<bead>`. No flags,
  no JSON assembly — it wraps the built binary + verify + push.

**Tests:** No Go code changes, so no unit tests. Verified in two phases:
1. **Script behaviour — THROWAWAY repo first (synthetic; per the isolation rule).** Before any
   real use, exercise `scripts/dogfood-gate-capture.sh` in a throwaway `git init` repo under /tmp:
   create a run (capture a stage), author a gate JSON, run the script, and confirm: it appends
   (manifest_version 3, gate present), the local verify-before-push assertion fires (test the
   FAILURE path too — a bad gate JSON must exit non-zero and NOT push), and a clean run pushes.
   This proves the mutating/push behaviour synthetically without touching real refs.
2. **Real demonstration — on THIS bead's OWN new run (real dogfood data).** During .4's normal
   post-close dogfood-capture, the run `refs/etude/runs/etude-roadmap.2.4` is created with its
   stages. Then author .4's OWN GateAttempt(s) from its real gate notes — the plan gate (codex
   BLOCK→GO + gemini BLOCK→GO across rounds, opus GO, pilms disregarded + failure_note +
   decision.degraded_reason) and the implement+final gate — with `reviewed_stages` citing .4's own
   stage names (artifact shas or name-only `artifact:""`), and run the script against
   `etude-roadmap.2.4`. Verify by reading manifest.json back from the ref: `manifest_version` 3,
   `gates` present with the attempt(s), pilms = lmstudio / qwen/qwen3.6-35b-a3b, original stages
   untouched, ref pushed. This is a genuinely NEW run AND real (not synthetic) dogfood data;
   backfilling pre-existing runs is bead .5.

**Docs:** The two dogfood planning docs above ARE the doc deliverable (acceptance #1-#3). No
user-facing CLI prose or generated reference changes — `docs/cli/etude_capture-gate.md` already
shipped in .2 and the command is unchanged. The runbook/protocol are planning notes under
docs/plans, so the "shipped docs describe implemented behavior" policy is satisfied (capture-gate
exists; pilms provider is real).

**Risks:**
- Writing a real ref: the demonstration writes only THIS bead's OWN new run
  (`refs/etude/runs/etude-roadmap.2.4`), not an old pushed ref — and only after the script's
  mutating/push behaviour is proven in a throwaway repo first, and only after the local
  verify-before-push assertion passes. capture-gate is additive + validates referential integrity
  + fails loudly without mutating on bad input. The `git fetch` + ExpectedOld CAS guards a stale
  tip.
- reviewed_stages artifact integrity: the gate JSON must cite an EXACT Output/Inputs sha of a real
  stage on .4's run, or use `artifact:""` name-only. Low risk, caught by validation if wrong.
- Scope: strictly the two docs + one new script + one demonstration capture on .4's own run. The
  Go capture-gate code stays untouched; backfilling pre-existing runs is bead .5, not here.

**Capture:**
- inputs: bead etude-roadmap.2.4 (description + acceptance), spec docs/plans/product/gate-reviewer-record-schema.md (§4 wire shape, §5 worked example, verdict semantics), internal/cli/capture.go (gateInputJSON DTOs — exact snake_case gate-file contract), scripts/dogfood-capture.sh (build-fresh + push pattern to mirror), docs/plans/dogfood/review-gate-runbook.md (Recording Results / Reruns / Result Classification), docs/plans/dogfood/capture-protocol.md (Review Gate Capture), bd show etude-roadmap.2.2 notes (real four-seat gate outcomes), etude run show etude-roadmap.2.2 (real stage names + artifact shas)
